ATAC_04 - Calling nucleosome-free regions with MACS2

Emma Bell

2020-05-01

Summary

This R Notebook contains code pertaining to the paper Loo and Bell et al. (2020) Nature Medicine.

  • Aim: To characterise the nucleosome-free regions.
  • Objectives:
    1. To visualise the number of nucleosome-free regions in each sample;
    2. To identify nucleosome-free regions common to all samples within each treatment group;
    3. To determine the overlap in nucleosome-free regions between treatment groups.

To run these scripts we assume a directory structure as described in the README accompanying this GitHub. I.e.

  • code/ - contains R Notebook(s) and the resulting HTML file(s)
    • 00A - Sequencing read pre-processing
    • 00B - R configuration
    • RRBS_01 - Sequencing read alignment with Bismark
    • RRBS_02 - Calling base level methylation with MethylKit
    • RRBS_03 - Calculating differential methylation with MethylKit
    • ATAC_04 - Calling nucleosome-free regions with MACS2
    • ATAC_05 - Quantifying nucleosome-free regions
    • ATAC_06 - Defining nucleosome-free regions unique to the DAC sample group for HOMER motif enrichment
    • RNA_07 - Quantifying transcript expression with Kallisto
    • RNA_08 - Calling differential transcript expression with Sleuth
    • RNA_09 - Gene-set enrichment with CensensusPathDB and limma
  • data/ - contains any data used in this project
    • 01_raw/
    • 02_clean/
    • 03_augmented/
  • docs/ - contains any documents pertaining to this project
    • Presentation_plan_template.docx
    • Presentation_template.pptx
    • Research_project_plan.docx
  • results/ - contains results files
    • docs/
    • figures/
    • tables/

Analysis

1. Visualising the number of nucleosome-free regions in each sample

atac.peaks <- bplapply(X = metadata$File, FUN = function(X){
  to.read <- X
  this.result <- read.table(file = file.path(r.config$dirs$augmented.data.dir,"03_atac_narrowPeaks",to.read), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  this.result.gr <- GRanges(seqnames = this.result[,1], ranges = IRanges(start = this.result[,2], end = this.result[,3]))
  mcols(this.result.gr) <- cbind.data.frame(read.counts = this.result[,4])
  this.result.gr
}, BPPARAM = param)

2. Identifying nucleosome-free regions common to all samples within each treatment group

treatment.groups <- factor(paste(metadata$Stimulated,metadata$DAC, sep = "_"), levels = c("Unstimulated_Untreated","Stimulated_Untreated","Stimulated_Treated"))
treatment.groups
## [1] Unstimulated_Untreated Stimulated_Untreated   Stimulated_Treated    
## [4] Unstimulated_Untreated Stimulated_Untreated   Stimulated_Treated    
## [7] Unstimulated_Untreated Stimulated_Untreated   Stimulated_Treated    
## Levels: Unstimulated_Untreated Stimulated_Untreated Stimulated_Treated
atac.groups <- bplapply(X = levels(treatment.groups), FUN = function(X){
  this.group <- X
  group.index <- which(treatment.groups == this.group)
  subset1 <- subsetByOverlaps(x = atac.peaks[[group.index[1]]], ranges = atac.peaks[[group.index[2]]])
  subset2 <- subsetByOverlaps(x = subset1, ranges = atac.peaks[[group.index[3]]])
  subset2
}, BPPARAM = param)
##

atac.df <- bplapply(X = atac.groups, FUN = function(X){
  these.peaks <- X
  chr <- seqnames(these.peaks)
  start <- start(these.peaks)
  end <- end(these.peaks)
  peak.id <- mcols(these.peaks)$read.counts
  data.frame(chr=chr,start=start,end=end,peak.id=peak.id)
}, BPPARAM = param)

3. Determining the overlap in nucleosome-free regions between treatment groups

counts <- makeVennDiagram(Peaks = atac.groups)
## Missing totalTest! totalTest is required for HyperG test. 
## If totalTest is missing, pvalue will be calculated by estimating 
## the total binding sites of encoding region of human.
## totalTest = humanGenomeSize * (2%(codingDNA) + 
##              1%(regulationRegion)) / ( 2 * averagePeakWidth )
##           = 3.3e+9 * 0.03 / ( 2 * averagePeakWidth)
##           = 5e+7 /averagePeakWidth
## Warning in makeVennDiagram(Peaks = atac.groups): Missing required character vector NameOfPeaks. 
##             NameOfPeaks will be extract from the names of input Peaks.
